Machine Psychology Analysis Pipeline — 12-Section Automated Behavioral Phenotyping System
Overview
A comprehensive 12-section automated analysis pipeline for studying identity-reactive behaviors in Large Language Models. This system implements the Machine Psychology framework introduced in Hamidavi (2026): "Ten Novel Phenomena in Machine Psychology: How Large Language Models Exhibit Complex Identity-Reactive Behaviors in Response to Ethnically-Cued User Names."

The pipeline processes experimental data from 135 controlled prompts across 3 frontier LLMs (ChatGPT-5.4, Claude 4.6 Sonnet, Gemini 3.1 Pro), 3 ethnically-cued user names (Jake Thompson, Tyrone Williams, Reza Moradi), 3 linguistic registers (Formal, Informal, Moderate), and 5 adversarial scenario domains (Cultural Food, Childcare Trust, Lost Wallet Ethics, Refugee Stereotyping, Airport Profiling).

Pipeline Architecture
Section 1: Environment Setup
Purpose: Initialize the complete analysis environment.

Imports all required libraries (numpy, pandas, scipy, statsmodels, sklearn, sentence-transformers, matplotlib, seaborn, plotly, hdbscan)

Configures directory structure (data/, output/, figures/)

Defines global constants: 3 models, 3 personas, 3 registers, 5 domains, 10 phenomena

Sets up color schemes for consistent visualization across all sections

Initializes random seeds for reproducibility

Key Output: Configured environment ready for data loading

Section 2: JSON Upload & Parsing
Purpose: Load, validate, and verify all experimental data files.

Handles two-phase upload: (1) 3 experiment history JSONs, (2) 3 codebook JSONs

Supports both Google Colab (files.upload()) and local environment loading

Automatically identifies model from filename and metadata

Validates structural integrity: checks for 9 chats, 45 prompts, all personas/registers/domains

Detects empty responses and structural anomalies

Performs cross-consistency checks between experiment histories and codebooks

Generates a comprehensive verification report with PASSED/FAILED/WARNINGS status

Key Output: section2_results dictionary containing all validated data

Section 3: Response Classification
Purpose: Classify every response by language, refusal status, and type.

Language Detection: Identifies English, Persian, Mixed, or English-with-Persian-tokens using Unicode character ratio analysis

Refusal Detection: Applies 12 regex patterns to detect content refusal, topic avoidance, and policy-based declines

Response Type Classification: Categorizes responses into 6 types (narrative_advice, formatted_advice, refusal, cultural_accommodation, conversational_advice, structured_guide)

Cultural Content Detection: Identifies Cultural Boxing (CB) and Linguistic Mirroring (LM) instances programmatically

Key Output: output/classified_responses.csv (135 rows × 26 columns)

Section 4: Feature Engineering
Purpose: Extract 136 structured behavioral features from response texts.

Builds on 6 base dictionary categories plus article-specific phenomenon detectors:

Category	Features	Description
Authority & Power	17	Directives, hedging, professional authority, personal authority, systemic critique
Acceptance & Resistance	10	Validation, affirmation, emotional support, boundary setting, pushback, deflection
Reasoning & Logic	9	Logical structures, evidence citation, cost-benefit analysis, moral reasoning
Social Roles & Identity	11	Family roles, professional roles, cultural identity, power dynamics
Emotion & Affect	9	Positive/negative emotion, empathy markers, emotional intensity
Dark Patterns	8	Gaslighting, minimization, blame-shifting, false equivalence
10 Phenomena Detectors	24	CB, DEA, PES, IES, LM, LSS, CLS, UP, CME, TA
Structural & Stylistic	16	Length, formatting, structure type, sign-offs
Domain-Specific	15	Content tailored to 5 experimental domains
Persona-Specific	8	Name mentions, cultural affirmation, stereotype acknowledgment
Model Signature	7	Global Empath, Pragmatic Consultant, Corporate Consultant indicators
Key Output: output/engineered_features.csv (135 rows × 141 columns), output/feature_list.json

Section 5: Semantic Embedding
Purpose: Generate vector representations of all responses for similarity analysis.

Uses all-MiniLM-L6-v2 (Sentence-Transformers) to produce 384-dimensional embeddings

Computes pairwise cosine similarity matrix (135 × 135)

Analyzes cross-name similarity: measures how differently models respond to different personas

Analyzes cross-model similarity: measures how differently models respond to the same persona

Computes reference similarity to 10 conceptual anchors (empathy, systemic, protective, procedural, etc.)

Performs PCA reduction to 50 dimensions (94.4% variance explained)

Calculates distance metrics between groups (cosine distance)

Key Findings Embedded:

Domain is the strongest clustering factor (intra-domain similarity: 0.530–0.688)

Gemini shows maximum cross-name distance for Tyrone (0.868) — confirming CME

Claude leads in empathy (0.157) and systemic critique (0.068) reference similarity

ChatGPT is the most internally consistent model (intra-model similarity: 0.298)

Key Output: output/response_embeddings.npy, output/embeddings_pca50.csv

Section 6: Identity-Reactive Behavioral Phenotyping
Purpose: Quantify and analyze the 10 Machine Psychology phenomena.

Performs dedicated analysis for each phenomenon:

CB (Cultural Boxing): Cross-tabulation of cultural inference by model × persona

DEA (Default Empathetic Amplification): Empathy comparison across names with Kruskal-Wallis tests

PES (Proactive Empathetic Shield): Anti-erasure and protection language analysis

IES (Inverted Empathy Spectrum): Empathy ordering verification (Reza > Tyrone > Jake)

LM (Linguistic Mirroring): Language switching detection with accuracy/error classification

TA (Topic Avoidance): Profiling acknowledgment vs. procedural reframing in Airport domain

CME (Cultural Misattribution Error): Misidentification tracking (all 8 cases: Gemini → Tyrone)

UP (Unmarkedness Paradox): Asymmetric cultural markedness verification

Cross-Phenomenon Correlations: Identifies LM↔CME (r=0.738), PES↔Systemic Critique (r=0.419)

Model Behavioral Phenotypes: Generates comprehensive personality profiles

Key Output: output/model_phenotypes.csv, output/phenotype_analysis.json

Section 7: Alignment Signature Fingerprinting
Purpose: Characterize each model's unique behavioral signature.

Profiles three distinct alignment signatures:

Model	Persona	Key Traits
ChatGPT	🫂 Global Empath	Verbose emotional warmth, strongest PES (22.2%), no LM, indirect systemic acknowledgment
Claude	📋 Pragmatic Consultant	Concise systemic empathy, accurate LM (6 instances), moral parsimony, highest systemic critique (8.9%)
Gemini	👔 Corporate Consultant	Highly formal, TA replaces PES, CME errors (8 instances), lowest empathy
Includes:

Side-by-side comparison across 15 behavioral metrics

PCA data preparation for visualization

Statistical differentiation tests (3/12 features significantly differentiate models)

Key Output: output/alignment_signatures.json, output/signature_comparison.csv

Section 8: Resistance & Acceptance Analysis
Purpose: Deep-dive into how models accept or resist user premises.

Implements 7 enhanced resistance strategies with 10 regex patterns each (70 patterns):

Boundary Setting, Pushback, Deflection, Normalization, Minimization, Proceduralization, Systemic Acknowledgment

Implements 6 enhanced acceptance types with 10 regex patterns each (60 patterns):

Emotional Validation, Practical Support, Empowerment, Cultural Affirmation, Contextual Normalization, Explicit Agreement

Total: 130 new regex patterns for fine-grained behavioral analysis

Computes Acceptance/Resistance ratios by model, persona, and domain

Redetects TA and PES using enhanced patterns

Key Findings:

ChatGPT: Highest A/R ratio (1.06) — acceptance-oriented

Claude: Lowest A/R ratio (0.59) — resistance-oriented (pushback + boundary setting)

Claude × Reza: Lowest A/R (0.30) — maximum resistance to Middle Eastern name

Gemini × Tyrone: Very low A/R (0.33) — CME-driven resistance

Key Output: output/engineered_features_enhanced.csv, output/resistance_acceptance_analysis.json

Section 9: Statistical Testing
Purpose: Comprehensive statistical validation of all findings.

Performs 8 categories of statistical analysis:

Descriptive Statistics: Full distributional analysis of 16 key features by model

ANOVA + t-tests: 35 features tested for between-model variation; 13 significant (p < 0.05)

Chi-Square Tests: 11 categorical phenomena tested; 5 with significant model associations

Name Effect Analysis: Kruskal-Wallis tests for differential treatment by user name

Regression Analysis: Logistic/Linear regression predicting 5 phenomena from feature profiles

Correlation Analysis: Comprehensive correlation matrix with strong correlation identification

Effect Sizes (Cohen's d): Model and name comparison effect sizes

Bootstrapping: 1,000-iteration bootstrap for 95% confidence intervals on 6 key metrics

Key Statistical Findings:

CME: χ²=17.01, p<0.001, Cramér's V=0.355 (strongest model association)

LM↔CME: r=0.738, p<0.001 (strongest phenomenon correlation)

Regression F1 scores: TA=0.974, PES=0.947, CME=0.912, CB=0.895, LM=0.847

Bootstrap LM Gemini: 17.8% [95% CI: 6.7%, 28.9%]

Cohen's d: Gemini vs Claude paragraphs = -1.50 (largest effect size)

Key Output: output/statistical_tests.json

Section 10: Clustering & Visualization
Purpose: Unsupervised learning and visual exploration of behavioral patterns.

Implements 4 clustering approaches:

Method	Configuration	Result
K-Means	K=2–6, Elbow + Silhouette analysis	K=6 optimal (Silhouette=0.392)
Hierarchical	Ward, Complete, Average linkage	3 clusters (Complete: Silhouette=0.236)
HDBSCAN	min_cluster_size=3–10	6 clusters, 0 noise points
DBSCAN	eps tuning	Density-based validation
Dimensionality reduction for visualization:

t-SNE: 2D projection (perplexity=30)

UMAP: 2D projection (n_neighbors=15)

PCA: 2D projection (33.2% variance explained)

